member.example:

var numbers = new[] { 123, 456, 789 };
var result = numbers.TagFirstLast();

The result variable, when iterated over, will yield
(item: 123, isFirst: True, isLast: False),
(item: 456, isFirst: False, isLast: False) and
(item: 789, isFirst: False, isLast: True) in turn.


var numbers = new[] { 123, 456, 789 };
var result = numbers.TagFirstLast((num, fst, lst) => new
             {
                 Number = num,
                 IsFirst = fst, IsLast = lst
             });

The result variable, when iterated over, will yield
{ Number = 123, IsFirst = True, IsLast = False },
{ Number = 456, IsFirst = False, IsLast = False } and
{ Number = 789, IsFirst = False, IsLast = True } in turn.


int[] numbers = { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 };
var result = numbers.TakeEvery(2);

The result variable, when iterated over, will yield 1, 3 and 5, in turn.

example.code:
Console.WriteLine(
    Enumerable
        .Range(1, 5)
        .WindowLeft(3)
        .Select(w => "AVG(" + w.ToDelimitedString(",") + ") = " + w.Average())
        .ToDelimitedString(Environment.NewLine));

// Output:
// AVG(1,2,3) = 2
// AVG(2,3,4) = 3
// AVG(3,4,5) = 4
// AVG(4,5) = 4.5
// AVG(5) = 5

Console.WriteLine(
    Enumerable
        .Range(1, 5)
        .WindowRight(3)
        .Select(w => "AVG(" + w.ToDelimitedString(",") + ") = " + w.Average())
        .ToDelimitedString(Environment.NewLine));

// Output:
// AVG(1) = 1
// AVG(1,2) = 1.5
// AVG(1,2,3) = 2
// AVG(2,3,4) = 3
// AVG(3,4,5) = 4
